from amino acids","Modify proteins with phosphate groups","Degrade ubiquitin-tagged proteins","Package proteins for secretion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of proteasomes is the \u003Cstrong\u003Edegradation of ubiquitin-tagged proteins\u003C/strong\u003E. Proteins marked for destruction are tagged with ubiquitin molecules and then recognised by the proteasome complex, which breaks them down into smaller peptides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport proteins across cell membranes\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by transport proteins and channels in the cell membrane\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesise new proteins from amino acids\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of ribosomes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModify proteins with phosphate groups\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by protein kinases\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPackage proteins for secretion\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by the Golgi apparatus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding proteasome function is clinically relevant as proteasome inhibitors like bortezomib are effective treatments for multiple myeloma and other cancers. Cancer cells often have increased protein turnover and are more dependent on proteasome function than normal cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Proteasomes are protein complexes that break down damaged or unneeded proteins tagged with ubiquitin.","The 26S proteasome consists of a 20S core particle and two 19S regulatory particles.","Proteasome inhibitors like bortezomib are effective cancer treatments because cancer cells are more dependent on protein degradation."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), 